  "answer": "The target's claim and mechanism do not predict that iron-rich polities would be immune to collapse, so the observation of severe disruption in iron-rich Anatolian highlands does not falsify the claim. The mechanism states that collapse severity correlates with dependence on Cypriot copper, not that iron self-sufficiency alone guarantees stability. The Hittite polity, including its iron-rich highland regions, was integrated into the same imperial fiscal-military system centered on Hattusa, which the target explicitly identifies as iron-poor and dependent on bronze inventories. Collapse of the central Hittite administrative and military apparatus would necessarily disrupt dependent highland regions regardless of their local iron resources, because ironworking at that time was not yet producing strategic quantities of carburized iron weapons to replace bronze military equipment at scale. The forbidden case as stated does not establish that the iron-rich highland polities were autarkic, institutionally independent, or capable of fielding iron-based militaries sufficient to resist the cascading effects of bronze depletion in the wider system. Therefore, the observation of severe disruption in those highlands is fully consistent with the target's mechanism and does not constitute a concrete falsification."
